<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910612-0118</DOCNO><DOCID>910612-0118.</DOCID><HL>   Economy:   U.S. Had Surplus   In Current Account   For First Quarter   ----   By Paul Duke Jr.   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)U.S. ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)</IN><NS>ECONOMIC NEWS, TRENDS, INDEXES, PROJECTIONS, ANALYSES (ECO)ECONOMIC RELEASES (EMI)</NS><GV>COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Donations from allies to cover the costs ofthe Persian Gulf War gave the U.S. its first overall tradesurplus in the first quarter since 1982.   The Commerce Department said $22.7 billion incontributions from allies helped push the current-accounttrade balance to a surplus of $10.2 billion in the firstthree months of the year, compared with a deficit of $23.4billion in the fourth quarter of 1990.</LP><TEXT>   The current-account figure, the broadest measure offoreign trade, covers merchandise trade as well as investmentincome, government payments and services such as tourism.   Excluding the war contributions, the current-accountdeficit was $12.5 billion, compared with $27.76 billion inthe fourth quarter of 1990. That continued an improving trendof recent years. Most of the change came in the balance onmerchandise trade, which narrowed to an $18.4 billion deficitin the first quarter from a $27.7 billion gap in last year'sfourth quarter. The surplus in services dropped roughly $500million, to $7 billion, while the surplus in investmentincome slipped about $1.5 billion, to $4.7 billion.   Through the end of March, the U.S. overall had received$37.15 billion in contributions, and pledges for anadditional $17.4 billion toward the cost of the war. TheDefense Department says that through the end of March the warcost $36.1 billion more than would have been spent otherwise;when repair, maintenance and other costs are tallied, itexpects the total will reach $60 billion.   The Commerce Department yesterday also released its annualrevisions of the current account data. The deficit for 1990was revised to $92.1 billion from the previous estimate of$99.3 billion. The 1989 gap was revised to $106.3 billionfrom the previous figure of $110 billion.   The first-quarter surplus was the first since the secondquarter of 1982, when the surplus was $3.6 billion.</TEXT></DOC>